comment.body:
@Krixano: I think no. According to these lines in `UiWebsocket.py`:
```python
    def actionSitePublish(self, to, privatekey=None, inner_path="content.json", sign=True):
        if sign:
            inner_path = self.actionSiteSign(to, privatekey, inner_path, response_ok=False)
            if not inner_path:
                return
```
...sign always happens before publishing. Anyway, I find that launching a site is difficult in ZeroNet because you have no peers. When there are at least 5 peers, everything is OK. Another reason to spread Git Center :)

@Krixano:
> Yes, I am. How did you guess?
I'm still waiting for an answer :)

@Krixano:
> For me, I start zeronet with the zeronet.exe file. Perhaps the reason for our differences is that your using an older version of the bundle?
Maybe **you** are using an old version? I've just downloaded a new version from here: https://github.com/HelloZeroNet/ZeroBundle/blob/master/dist/ZeroBundle-win.zip ...and I have Python and ZeroNet folder after running `zeronet.cmd`.

@Krixano:
> no, I left it at it's default state. But that shouldn't matter should it?
That shouldn't matter at all. I just mean that you didn't do anything that I didn't receive.

@Krixano:
> And, the log tab isn't loading the commits anymore. Also, the log page doesn't have all of the tabs listed at the top.
Fixed. There was no `Releases` tab, so there was something like null pointer exception, and logs weren't loaded.

@Krixano:
> I think all tags, regardless of if they are annotated or not are shown in the releases tab (not sure if this is actually how you want it though).
I thought that Git Center should show all tags, but unannotated tags would have no title and description. Maybe you can give a better idea?

@Krixano:
> Also, I recommend muting qubesi2p@zeroid.bit
I've just read that thread on ZeroTalk.

@Krixano:
> Well, I was originally thinking that after the user created the tag, they then click a button on the zite to create a release and give it the tag name. That way they can tell the zite which tags are releases and which aren't.
And if just making a button `Mark tag "..." as release` which will accept annotated tags?

@Krixano:
> btw, tell me if I'm pestering you with too many things to do
Nope. It's wonderful when someone is interested in your project!

@Krixano:
> Add the ability to see what was changed in a commit.
Like diff?

@Krixano:
> Another thing, blocking people from creating issues and pull requests.
You can mute them in `data/users/content.json` of your repository. Maybe add it to `Settings` tab?
